    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize if the \"thieves\" analogy was a bit too... creative. Let's stick to the numbers, shall we?\n\nThe daily interest rate is calculated by dividing the monthly interest rate by 365 (or 366 in leap years). For example, if your loan has a 6% monthly interest rate, the daily interest rate would be:\n\n6% / 365 ≈ 0.0164% per day\n\nThis means that for every day that passes, the interest on your loan would accrue approximately 0.0164% of the outstanding balance.\n\nTo calculate the daily interest, you can multiply the outstanding balance by the daily interest rate. For instance, if your balance is $10,000, the daily interest would be:\n\n$10,000 x 0.0164% ≈ $1.64 per day\n\nNow, when you make your monthly payment, you're essentially subtracting the principal and interest from the outstanding balance. The interest is calculated on the new balance, which is why it can take a while for the principal to decrease significantly.\n\nTo illustrate this, let's say you pay $1,000 in principal and interest on a $10,000 balance. The interest for the month would be approximately",
